</style>
    <div class="container">
        <h1 class="text-left display-4">The Latin Berber Alphabet</h1>
        <p class="text-left lead">The Berber alphabet is derived from the Latin alphabet. This alphabet is the creation of the Kabyle-origin Berber linguist, Mouloud Mammeri, and was definitively established in 1973. Mouloud Mammeri's alphabet, also called the Tamɛemmrit, consists of 23 standard Latin letters and 10 additional letters.</p>
        <p class="text-left lead">Today, the Latin Berber alphabet is the most widely used alphabet to transcribe the different regional variants of the Berber language. Indeed, the use of Tamɛemmrit by Berber-speaking writers has become a norm, although this alphabet does not have any official recognition in Morocco and Algeria. In Morocco, the official alphabet to transcribe Berber is Tifinagh, which is, however, sparsely used and not widespread within the Berber-speaking community.</p>
    </div>
</div>

